04919nam a22005655i 9780822379577DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20131996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223795777 a10.1515/97808223795772doi  a(DE-B1597)551866  a(OCoLC)1202624503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGN357.D57 1996eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a30622300aDisplacement, Diaspora, and Geographies of Identity /cTed Swedenburg, Smadar Lavie. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b6 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: DISPLACEMENT, DIASPORA, AND GEOGRAPHIES OF IDENTITY -- tLIVING WITH MIRACLES: THE POLITICS AND POETICS OF WRITING AMERICAN INDIAN RESISTANCE AND IDENTITY -- tANZALDUA'S FRONTERA: INSCRIBING GYNETICS -- tBLOWUPS IN THE BORDERZONES: THIRD WORLD ISRAELI AUTHORS' GROPINGS FOR HOME -- tTHE NARRATIVE PRODUCTION OF "HOME," COMMUNITY, AND POLITICAL IDENTITY IN ASIAN AMERICAN THEATER -- tARAB NOISE AND RAMADAN NIGHTS: RAI, RAP, AND FRANCO-MAGHREBI IDENTITIES -- tTOURISM IN THE BALINESE BORDERZONE -- tSONGS LODGED IN SOME HEARTS: DISPLACEMENTS OF WOMEN'S KNOWLEDGE IN KANGRA -- t"CULTURAL DEFENSE" AND CRIMINOLOGICAL DISPLACEMENTS:GENDER,RACE,AND (TRANS)NATION IN THE LEGAL SURVEILLANCE OF U.S. DIASPORA ASIANS -- tTHE FIGURE OF THE X: AN ELABORATION OF THE DU BOISIAN AUTOBIOGRAPHICAL EXAMPLE -- tCROSSCURRENTS, CROSSTALK: RACE, "POSTCOLONIALITY," AND THE POLITICS OF LOCATION -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tContributors 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisplacement, Diaspora, and Geographies of Identity challenges conventional understandings of identity based on notions of nation and culture as bounded or discrete. Through careful examinations of various transnational, hybrid, border, and diasporic forces and practices, these essays push at the edge of cultural studies, postmodernism, and postcolonial theory and raise crucial questions about ethnographic methodology.This volume exemplifies a cross-disciplinary cultural studies and a concept of culture rooted in lived experience as well as textual readings. Anthropologists and scholars from related fields deploy a range of methodologies and styles of writing to blur and complicate conventional dualisms between authors and subjects of research, home and away, center and periphery, and first and third world. Essays discuss topics such as Rai, a North African pop music viewed as westernized in Algeria and as Arab music in France; the place of Sephardic and Palestinian writers within Israel's Ashkenazic-dominated arts community; and the use and misuse of the concept "postcolonial" as it is applied in various regional contexts.In exploring histories of displacement and geographies of identity, these essays call for the reconceptualization of theoretical binarisms such as modern and postmodern, colonial and postcolonial. It will be of interest to a broad spectrum of scholars and students concerned with postmodern and postcolonial theory, ethnography, anthropology, and cultural studies.Contributors. Norma Alarcón, Edward M. Bruner, Nahum D. Chandler, Ruth Frankenberg, Joan Gross, Dorinne Kondo, Kristin Koptiuch, Smadar Lavie, Lata Mani, David McMurray, Kirin Narayan, Greg Sarris, Ted Swedenburg  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCulturevCase studies. 0aCulturexCase studies. 0aEthnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aLavie, Smadar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSwedenburg, Ted, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 19